## 🚨 Finding 1 — Broken Access Control (OWASP A01:2021) — **HIGH**

**`/users` exposes PII with zero authentication or authorization.**

```js
// CURRENT — anyone on the internet can call this
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' },
  ]);
});
```

Email addresses are Personally Identifiable Information (PII). There is no check for who is calling this endpoint — no token, no session, no role.

**✅ Recommended fix:**

```js
// Add authentication middleware (example using JWT)
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const authHeader = req.headers['authorization'];
  const token = authHeader && authHeader.split(' ')[1]; // Bearer <token>

  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });

  jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, (err, user) => {
    if (err) return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
    req.user = user;
    next();
  });
}

// Apply to protected routes
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only authorized users reach here
  res.json([ /* ... */ ]);
});
```

---

## 🚨 Finding 2 — Security Misconfiguration / Information Disclosure (OWASP A05:2021) — **HIGH**

**Express advertises itself via the `X-Powered-By: Express` response header by default.** This tells attackers exactly what server technology and framework you're running, making targeted exploit selection trivial.

Additionally, no security headers are set (no CSP, HSTS, X-Frame-Options, etc.).

**✅ Recommended fix — add `helmet`:**

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');

// Must be the FIRST middleware registered
app.use(helmet());
// helmet() automatically sets:
//   X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
//   X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN
//   Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)
//   Content-Security-Policy
//   Referrer-Policy
//   ... and removes X-Powered-By
```

Install with: `npm install helmet`

---

## 🚨 Finding 3 — No Rate Limiting (OWASP A07:2021 / DoS) — **HIGH**

There is **no rate limiting on any endpoint.** This enables:
- Credential stuffing / brute-force (when auth is added)
- Denial of Service via request flooding
- User enumeration by scraping `/users` at high speed

**✅ Recommended fix — add `express-rate-limit`:**

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // max 100 requests per window per IP
  standardHeaders: true,     // Return rate limit info in RateLimit-* headers
  legacyHeaders: false,
  message: { error: 'Too many requests, please try again later.' },
});

// Apply globally
app.use(limiter);

// Apply stricter limits to sensitive endpoints
const strictLimiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 10 });
app.get('/users', strictLimiter, requireAuth, ...);
```

Install with: `npm install express-rate-limit`

